1
00:00:00,638 --> 00:00:30,155
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

2
00:00:32,515 --> 00:00:59,585
so we've now got to the end of this discourse the turning of the wheel of the law and we've been through the opening where he's pointing out what the middle path is so it's nothing it's not to do with indulging in the wonders of life nor is it to do with some form of self-mortification we went through the first the noble truths truth of suffering

3
00:01:00,646 --> 00:01:08,373
the reason for suffering, the cause of suffering, the arising of suffering, the cessation of suffering, which is nibbana, and the path.

4
00:01:09,334 --> 00:01:16,400
So now he tells us what to do with each of these noble truths.

5
00:01:17,141 --> 00:01:20,424
So the first one is, of course, just a basic statement.

6
00:01:20,983 --> 00:01:25,007
He then tells us what we have to do, and then he tells us that he's done it.

7
00:01:27,530 --> 00:01:30,653
So he says, this is the noble truth of suffering, so we've been through that.

8
00:01:31,341 --> 00:01:34,165
The noble truth of suffering is to be fully understood.

9
00:01:34,185 --> 00:01:36,007
To be fully understood.

10
00:01:36,447 --> 00:01:39,650
And remember that the understanding is in three phases.

11
00:01:39,810 --> 00:01:44,295
It's both in the phase of something that you hear and understand.

12
00:01:45,436 --> 00:01:50,021
And then it's the phase of understanding it because you yourself have reflected on it.

13
00:01:50,040 --> 00:01:52,283
So it's become your own intellectual knowledge.

14
00:01:53,144 --> 00:01:58,429
And then it's understood at a deeper level by direct experience through vipassana, through insight.

15
00:01:59,405 --> 00:02:25,985
so that's what he means when he says the noble truth of suffering is to be fully understood then he says the noble truth of suffering has been fully understood see by him thus monks in regard to things unheard of before there arose in me vision knowledge wisdom penetration and light then

16
00:02:26,606 --> 00:02:55,229
he again states it this is the noble truth of the origin of suffering you can translate it also as the cause of suffering so this noble truth of the origin of suffering has to be abandoned so the cause of suffering is desire now remember it's a desire which is based on seeking happiness in the wrong place seeking happiness in the sensual world when the Buddha says the sensual world he means anything to do with what we experience

17
00:02:56,391 --> 00:03:01,197
because the senses, remember, are basically your five normal senses.

18
00:03:01,217 --> 00:03:02,217
It's also the mind.

19
00:03:03,118 --> 00:03:06,663
So when he talks about the sensual world, he's also talking about these absorptions.

20
00:03:07,223 --> 00:03:11,247
So it's anything in the phenomenal world has to be abandoned.

21
00:03:12,049 --> 00:03:20,938
Remember, it's not that they're destroyed, it's just that it's the desire that has to be abandoned for them, arising from this wrong relationship.

22
00:03:22,341 --> 00:03:23,681
And then he states quite clearly,

23
00:03:24,133 --> 00:03:51,372
the noble truth of the origin of suffering has been abandoned he's done it then he says this is the noble truth of the cessation of suffering now the noble truth of the cessation of suffering is to be realized in other words this one is the realization of nirvana it's an experience it's an actual experience of something

24
00:03:51,606 --> 00:04:21,427
which just simply doesn't belong to this phenomenal world it's something beyond it and that's what Nibbāna is Nibbāna itself, remember, is a word which is was used with fire, with heat so he's talking about consciousness he's talking about the way consciousness wraps itself around something gets stuck on something and when he talks about the light going out the fire going out, the flame going out Nibbāna he's always talking about the release of consciousness so remember that in those days

25
00:04:21,795 --> 00:04:45,930
the physics wasn't the same as ours the idea was that you had a fuel and that when you did certain things to this fuel it drew the fire element from the universe so if you rub two sticks together you're actually beckoning this fire element to congeal around the wood and when of course

26
00:04:46,314 --> 00:04:48,697
the wood finished, what happened to the fire element?

27
00:04:49,178 --> 00:04:53,444
It didn't die out, it just went back into that state of potential.

28
00:04:53,464 --> 00:04:57,170
So nibbana is that unbinding of consciousness.

29
00:04:57,831 --> 00:05:00,295
It's the unbinding of it, the release of it.

30
00:05:01,317 --> 00:05:03,660
And how does that tightness manifest?

31
00:05:03,839 --> 00:05:06,543
Desire, attachment.

32
00:05:06,564 --> 00:05:08,185
Simple, isn't it?

33
00:05:08,206 --> 00:05:15,596
And then he says, of course, that this noble truth of the way leading to the cessation of suffering, sorry, sorry,

34
00:05:15,846 --> 00:05:20,793
The noble truth of the cessation of suffering has been realized.

35
00:05:21,413 --> 00:05:32,747
Thus, monks, in regard to things unheard of before, there arose in me vision, knowledge, wisdom, penetration, and light.

36
00:05:32,767 --> 00:05:35,490
And then the fourth noble truth is a simple statement.

37
00:05:35,790 --> 00:05:42,259
This noble truth of the way leading to the cessation of suffering is to be developed.

38
00:05:43,927 --> 00:06:11,875
the noble truth of the way leading to the cessation of suffering is to be developed so in other words the process of moving from a state of unenlightenment a state of unhappiness to a state of happiness is to be developed in other words it's gradual and he's very sort of insistent that the process is gradual

39
00:06:12,732 --> 00:06:16,675
It's very rare for somebody just to make it just like that.

40
00:06:17,177 --> 00:06:20,000
Remember the story of Bahir of the bark cloth.

41
00:06:20,019 --> 00:06:32,331
Now, Bahir, of course, was enlightened just upon hearing this immediate teaching that in the hearing there's only the hearing, in the seeing there's only the seeing, in the cognizing there's only the cognizing.

42
00:06:32,612 --> 00:06:39,819
But then you have to remember he'd been living with this bark cloth for years and being separated from the world, not indulging.

43
00:06:42,026 --> 00:06:43,488
in Costa Coffee or anything like that.

44
00:06:46,011 --> 00:06:51,536
And so then he says, this noble truth leading to the sedation of suffering has been developed.

45
00:06:51,896 --> 00:07:00,507
Thus, monks, in regards to things unheard of before, there arose in me vision, knowledge, wisdom, penetration, and light.

46
00:07:02,788 --> 00:07:04,149
And then there's this lovely section.

47
00:07:04,370 --> 00:07:10,396
So long, monks, as my knowledge and vision of these four noble truths, as they really are,

48
00:07:10,798 --> 00:07:29,680
in the three phases and twelve aspects, was not thoroughly purified in this way, I did not claim to have awakened to the unsurpassed perfect enlightenment in this world, with its deva, mara and brahma, in this population, with its ascetics and brahmins, its devas and humans.

49
00:07:30,240 --> 00:07:40,451
But, when my knowledge and vision of these four noble truths, as they really are, in their three phases and twelve aspects, was thoroughly purified in this way,

50
00:07:41,107 --> 00:07:53,906
Then I claimed to have awakened to the unsurpassed perfect enlightenment in this world with its devas, mara and brahma, in this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its devas and humans.

51
00:07:54,747 --> 00:07:56,951
The knowledge and vision arose in me.

52
00:07:57,872 --> 00:08:00,737
Unshakable is the liberation of my mind.

53
00:08:01,798 --> 00:08:03,420
This is my last birth.

54
00:08:04,362 --> 00:08:06,966
Now there is no more renewed becoming.

55
00:08:07,608 --> 00:08:07,687
Hmm?

56
00:08:08,444 --> 00:08:11,286
Unshakeable is the liberation of my mind.

57
00:08:14,151 --> 00:08:15,752
This is what the Blessed One said.

58
00:08:16,052 --> 00:08:20,619
Elated, the monks of the group of five delighted in the Blessed One's statement.

59
00:08:21,500 --> 00:08:29,649
And while this discourse was being spoken, there arose in the Venerable Kondanya the dust-free, stainless vision of the Dhamma.

60
00:08:30,589 --> 00:08:35,255
Whatever is subject to origination is all subject to cessation.

61
00:08:35,275 --> 00:08:37,759
So, here while he's speaking,

62
00:08:38,092 --> 00:08:44,019
One of his old companions has an insight into this impermanence.

63
00:08:45,461 --> 00:08:48,404
And he sees that whatever arises passes away.

64
00:08:49,547 --> 00:08:56,615
And it's deep enough for him to have a change in the way that he relates to the world.

65
00:09:01,139 --> 00:09:07,628
Now, when the wheel of the dhamma had been set in motion by the Blessed One,

66
00:09:08,620 --> 00:09:10,783
This is the crescendo bit.

67
00:09:10,803 --> 00:09:11,224
You're waiting.

68
00:09:15,250 --> 00:09:22,162
And when the wheel of the Dhamma had been set in motion by the Blessed One, the earth-dwelling Devas raised a cry.

69
00:09:23,124 --> 00:09:31,336
At Baranasi, in the deer park of Isipatana, this unsurpassed wheel of the Dhamma has been set in motion by the Blessed One,

70
00:09:31,705 --> 00:09:39,173
which cannot be stopped by any ascetic, or Brahmin, or Deva, or Mara, or Brahma, or by anyone in this world.

71
00:09:40,155 --> 00:09:47,203
And having heard the cry of the earth-dwelling Devas, the Devas of the realm of the four great kings raised the cry.

72
00:09:47,245 --> 00:09:58,759
And having raised the cry, the Devas of the realm of the four great kings, the Tavatimsa Devas, the Yama Devas, the Tusita Devas, the Devas who delight in creating,

73
00:09:59,177 --> 00:10:21,542
the devas who wield power over others' creations, the devas of Brahma's company raised a cry at Baranasi in the deer park at Isipatana, this unsurpassed wheel of the Dhamma had been set in motion by the Blessed One, which cannot be stopped by any ascetic or Brahmin or deva or Mara or Brahma or by anyone in this world.

74
00:10:24,024 --> 00:10:24,565
Moving, isn't it?

75
00:10:26,967 --> 00:10:28,188
Thus at that moment,

76
00:10:28,708 --> 00:10:45,636
At that instant, at that second, the cry spread as far as the Brahma world, and this ten-thousand-world system, shook, quaked and trembled, and an immeasurable great radiance, surpassing the divine majesty of the Devas, appeared in the world.

77
00:10:47,860 --> 00:10:55,273
Then the Blessed One uttered this inspired utterance, Kondanya has indeed understood, Kondanya knows,

78
00:10:55,927 --> 00:11:00,894
In this way, the Venerable Kondanya acquired the name Anya Kondanya.

79
00:11:01,495 --> 00:11:03,697
Kondanya, the one who knows.

80
00:11:05,561 --> 00:11:06,101
Good stuff, eh?

81
00:11:08,063 --> 00:11:17,176
Now, I think it's just good to reflect on that moment there when the Buddha realizes that Kondanya actually understands.

82
00:11:17,216 --> 00:11:25,868
So remember, not so long before this, he's had this experience of liberation, complete liberation.

83
00:11:26,658 --> 00:11:56,596
and he wants to teach it and he has a doubt as to whether anybody can grasp the subtlety of this so now here he is he's met his companions and he's given them this teaching and one person actually he recognizes one person has actually had this insight into impermanence which he sees as liberating he sees that actually Kondanya can has made

84
00:11:57,320 --> 00:11:59,623
has made a glimpse into Nibbāna, okay?

85
00:12:00,764 --> 00:12:16,501
Now anybody who's done any teaching even if it's just to your children or to somebody at work and you've been sort of explaining something and they've had a bit of difficulty understanding and then suddenly they grasp it, see?

86
00:12:16,841 --> 00:12:19,004
Doesn't joy arise in your heart?

87
00:12:19,024 --> 00:12:19,225
You see?

88
00:12:19,745 --> 00:12:26,533
So one can only imagine the immeasurable reciprocal joy, the mudita

89
00:12:26,985 --> 00:12:33,553
that the Buddha must have felt when he realized that one of his old companions had actually made this insight.

90
00:12:33,573 --> 00:12:38,379
Because what had been a personal experience now becomes universal.

91
00:12:38,779 --> 00:12:42,404
If Kāṇḍañña can do it, so can everybody else.

92
00:12:42,424 --> 00:12:55,120
So it's just that little bit of the ending contemplation of the great joy within the Buddha when he realizes that in fact other people can grasp it, other people can be liberated.

93
00:12:58,423 --> 00:13:21,618
So I can only hope that this has also been an inspiration for you and that our little exegesis concerning the first discourse of the Buddha will inspire you to further effort and that you will be liberated from all your suffering sooner rather than later.

94
00:13:22,418 --> 00:13:23,841
Sadhu, sadhu, sadhu.

